    "visualization_explanation": "The dataset contains two-dimensional meteorological observations with categorical temporal grouping (months) and continuous temperature measurements. Synthetic data follows northern hemisphere mid-latitude seasonal patterns with winter lows (\u03bc=-5\u00b0C, \u03c3=4\u00b0C) and summer highs (\u03bc=23\u00b0C, \u03c3=5\u00b0C), maintaining realistic inter-diurnal ranges (8-12\u00b0C). Data generation incorporated annual temperature cyclicity with Gaussian noise (\u03c3=1.5\u00b0C) to simulate natural variability.\n\nThe 3D column range visualization effectively encodes minimum/maximum temperatures through vertical position and range length. While 3D projection reduces precision compared to 2D, it provides volumetric emphasis on seasonal amplitude differences. Color saturation reinforces temperature magnitude perception. The design maintains Cairo's principle of proportional ink by aligning column widths to month durations, and Tufte's data-ink ratio is preserved through minimal gridlines and uncluttered baseline."
